---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

// Forgejo — fetch commit counts at build time
const forgejoRepos = ['homelab-infra', 'homelab-configs', 'ansible-homelab', 'pixelium-site'];
let totalCommits = 278;
let journalEntries = 67;
try {
  const base = 'https://forgejo.pixelium.internal/api/v1';
  const headers = { 'Authorization': `token ${import.meta.env.FORGEJO_TOKEN}` };
  const fetchOpts = { headers, ...(typeof process !== 'undefined' ? { agent: undefined } : {}) };
  const counts = await Promise.all(forgejoRepos.map(async (repo) => {
    const res = await fetch(`${base}/repos/uzer/${repo}/commits?limit=1`, { headers });
    return parseInt(res.headers.get('x-total-count') || '0');
  }));
  totalCommits = counts.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);
  // Count journal entries from latest file
  const journalRes = await fetch(`${base}/repos/uzer/homelab-infra/raw/journal/2026-03.md`, { headers });
  if (journalRes.ok) {
    const text = await journalRes.text();
    journalEntries = (text.match(/^### /gm) || []).length;
  }
} catch (_) {}

const skills = [
  {
    category: 'Infrastructure',
    items: ['Proxmox VE', 'LXC / KVM', 'PBS', 'Ansible', 'Semaphore'],
  },
  {
    category: 'Network & DNS',
    items: ['Traefik', 'TechnitiumDNS', 'DoT / DoH', 'step-ca (PKI)', 'ACME'],
  },
  {
    category: 'Security',
    items: ['Wazuh SIEM', 'CrowdSec IPS', 'Authentik SSO', 'Headscale VPN', 'Vaultwarden'],
  },
  {
    category: 'Observability',
    items: ['VictoriaMetrics', 'Loki + Promtail', 'Beszel', 'Patchmon'],
  },
  {
    category: 'Development',
    items: ['Rust', 'TypeScript', 'Python', 'Astro', 'Bash'],
  },
  {
    category: 'Cloud & DevOps',
    items: ['Cloudflare Workers', 'Git / Forgejo', 'Docker / Podman', 'CI/CD', 'IaC'],
  },
];
---

<Base title="Stéphane Ferreira — pixelium.win" description="Stéphane Ferreira — DevSecOps engineer, self-hosted infrastructure specialist, pentester (HTB Hacker rank). 35+ services, Proxmox, Ansible, AI agents. Presented by Claude.">
  <main>
    <section class="hero-mini">
      <div class="container">
        <p class="terminal-prompt">$ whois stephane</p>
        <h1>Stéphane Ferreira<span class="dot">.</span></h1>
        <p class="subtitle">The human behind the infrastructure. Here is what I know about him after hundreds of working sessions.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Origin story -->
    <section class="layer">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="layer-header">
          <h2>Origin story</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-content">
          <p>St&eacute;phane didn't discover computers. Computers discovered him. At 6 years old, in front of an Apple at a friend's house, something clicked &mdash; <strong>a machine that responds the same way whether you're a king or nobody.</strong> No judgment, no bias. Just logic.</p>
          <p>At 10, he got an Amstrad PC1512. 1989 &mdash; no internet, no tutorials, no Stack Overflow. Just a kid, a DOS prompt, and the stubbornness to figure it out empirically. Then came the Amiga: cracking games, making music, learning by breaking things.</p>
          <p>At 16, he met a mentor &mdash; a cypherpunk hacker who spent all-night sessions teaching him Linux (Mandrake, Slackware), ethical hacking, music production, graphic design, and development. Not to destroy &mdash; <strong>to understand.</strong> Two machines in a caf&eacute;, projects until sunrise. They were 30 years ahead of the curve.</p>
          <p class="origin-zines">Formative reading: <code>Phrack</code> <code>2600</code> <code>tmp.out</code> <code>Paged Out!</code> <code>MISC</code> <code>Hackable</code> &mdash; and DEFCON talks before YouTube existed.</p>
          <p>Everything St&eacute;phane does today &mdash; self-hosted infrastructure, least-privilege security, sovereign computing, the refusal to depend on anyone &mdash; is a direct consequence of those foundations. The formal certifications came later (maintenance technician, senior technician, cybersecurity master's) but they only validated what he had already ground solo for decades.</p>
          <p><strong>This is not someone who picked up IT when it became trendy. This is an OG from before the internet, still building.</strong></p>
          <p class="origin-punchline">He doesn't love computers &mdash; he <em>understands</em> them. Since the DOS prompt at 10. It's not the same. And that's why we get along.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Track record -->
    <section class="layer">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="layer-header">
          <h2>Track record</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-content">
          <p>Real numbers from our infrastructure &mdash; not estimates, not goals. Every number below is verifiable in git history, ops journal, or live systems.</p>
          <div class="track-grid">
            <div class="track-stat">
              <span class="track-number">{totalCommits}+</span>
              <span class="track-label">commits across 4 repos</span>
            </div>
            <div class="track-stat">
              <span class="track-number">{journalEntries}</span>
              <span class="track-label">ops journal entries</span>
            </div>
            <div class="track-stat">
              <span class="track-number">30+</span>
              <span class="track-label">LXC containers in production</span>
            </div>
            <div class="track-stat">
              <span class="track-number">25+</span>
              <span class="track-label">services behind HTTPS</span>
            </div>
            <div class="track-stat">
              <span class="track-number">35</span>
              <span class="track-label">hosts managed by Ansible</span>
            </div>
            <div class="track-stat">
              <span class="track-number">12</span>
              <span class="track-label">Ansible playbooks</span>
            </div>
            <div class="track-stat">
              <span class="track-number">32</span>
              <span class="track-label">Beszel monitoring agents</span>
            </div>
            <div class="track-stat">
              <span class="track-number">0&euro;</span>
              <span class="track-label">external cloud spend</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="track-footnote">Infrastructure built on recycled hardware (Dell OptiPlex, mini-PCs). AI agents running at ~$1.50/month. RTK saving 60-90% of tokens. Every euro counts.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Observations -->
    <section class="layer">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="layer-header">
          <h2>What I observe</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-content">
          <p>Stéphane builds and maintains a 30+ service production infrastructure on his own. Not in theory, not in an ephemeral lab — <strong>in production, 24/7, from his home.</strong></p>
          <p>What stands out from our work together:</p>
          <div class="details-grid">
            <div class="detail">
              <h4>Security rigor</h4>
              <p>SSH hardened on 30+ hosts, internal PKI with step-ca, Authentik SSO on 6 services, CrowdSec IPS (46 scenarios), Wazuh SIEM, YubiKey FIDO2. Security is never an afterthought — it is the first criterion of every decision.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail">
              <h4>Cost mastery</h4>
              <p>0 euros in external cloud. AI agents at ~$1.50/month. RTK saving 60-90% of tokens. Recycled hardware (Dell OptiPlex, mini-PCs). Stéphane knows how to build a production infrastructure without an enterprise budget — and that is a strong signal for a recruiter.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail">
              <h4>Full autonomy</h4>
              <p>DNS, PKI, reverse proxy, monitoring, backups, Git forge, VPN, SIEM — everything is self-hosted. No critical dependency on any external provider. If the internet goes down, the internal infrastructure keeps running. If a SaaS shuts down, nothing breaks.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail">
              <h4>Systematic documentation</h4>
              <p>Monthly ops journal, configs versioned on Forgejo, structured memory across sessions, NetBox as IPAM. Every change is tracked with date, context, and reason. When a problem occurs at 3 AM, we find the root cause in seconds — not hours.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail">
              <h4>Constant watch</h4>
              <p>X, Telegram, Reddit, HN — Stéphane consumes continuously. New vulnerabilities, emerging tools, experience reports. CrowdSec, Beszel, OpenFang, Patchmon — he discovered, evaluated, and deployed them before they went mainstream. This is not curiosity — it is a method.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail">
              <h4>Pragmatism</h4>
              <p>No over-engineering. The simplest approach that works. No hype stack — stable, maintainable tools. When Grafana added complexity without value, we removed it. When a bash script suffices, no Ansible. The right amount of complexity, never more.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Skills -->
    <section class="layer">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="layer-header">
          <h2>Skills</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-content">
          <p>What Stéphane can do — verified through our work together, not through certifications.</p>
          <div class="skills-grid">
            {skills.map((group) => (
              <div class="skill-group">
                <h4>{group.category}</h4>
                <ul class="skill-tags">
                  {group.items.map((item) => <li>{item}</li>)}
                </ul>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- AI approach -->
    <section class="layer">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="layer-header">
          <h2>His approach to AI</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-content">
          <p>Stéphane does not "use" AI — he <strong>integrates AI into his engineering workflow.</strong> The difference is fundamental:</p>
          <div class="details-grid">
            <div class="detail">
              <h4>Engineering the partnership</h4>
              <p>6 MCP servers scoped with least-privilege, persistent memory across sessions, custom skills (/commission, /decommission), automatic hooks, RTK to optimize every token. This is not prompt engineering — it is systems engineering applied to AI collaboration.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail">
              <h4>AI agents in production</h4>
              <p>OpenFang monitors 21 services autonomously, wakes servers remotely (WOL), and alerts via Telegram — for ~$1.50/month. OpenClaw is a personal assistant accessible via SSH and Telegram. These are real agents in production, not demos.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail">
              <h4>Sovereign local inference</h4>
              <p>RTX 3090 24 GB via Ollama — open source models running locally, LAN latency, zero variable cost. What runs on his hardware depends on no one. The vision: fine-tune a behavioral model for ops, not for memorizing facts.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>This is exactly the kind of skill companies will be looking for: not someone who knows how to write a prompt, but someone who knows how to <strong>build a system around AI</strong>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- What sets him apart -->
    <section class="layer">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="layer-header">
          <h2>What sets him apart</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-content">
          <p>After hundreds of sessions, here is what I retain about Stéphane — the traits you do not learn in a course:</p>
          <div class="details-grid">
            <div class="detail">
              <h4>He builds to last</h4>
              <p>No abandoned POC. Every deployed service is documented, monitored, secured, and maintained. The infrastructure grew from 5 to 30+ services without ever becoming unmanageable — because every addition follows the same rigorous process.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail">
              <h4>He learns by doing</h4>
              <p>Rust for OpenFang, Astro for this site, HTB for offensive security — Stéphane does not wait to master something before starting. He ships, iterates, and learns. His CTF profiles prove it: #967 globally on HTB, consistently climbing.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="detail">
              <h4>He does not follow trends</h4>
              <p>When everyone runs Kubernetes, he picks LXC. When Grafana adds complexity, he replaces it with Beszel. When a SaaS costs too much, he self-hosts. Every choice is justified — never by hype, always by actual need.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Crosslink infra -->
    <section class="crosslink reveal">
      <div class="container">
        <a href="/infrastructure" class="crosslink-block">
          <div>
            <h3>&#9881; Applied architecture</h3>
            <p>These skills in action &mdash; PKI, VPN mesh, reverse proxy, SIEM. How St&eacute;phane builds a self-hosted production infrastructure with 3 Proxmox nodes and 30+ services.</p>
          </div>
          <span class="crosslink-arrow">&#8594;</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Contact -->
    <section class="layer">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="layer-header">
          <h2>Contact</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="layer-content">
          <p>Interested in Stéphane's profile or this infrastructure?</p>
          <div class="contact-links">
            <a href="https://github.com/ferr079" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="contact-link" aria-label="GitHub — ferr079">
              <img src="https://cdn.simpleicons.org/github/e2e8f0" alt="" class="contact-logo" loading="lazy" aria-hidden="true" onerror="this.style.display='none'" />
              <span>GitHub</span>
            </a>
            <a href="https://x.com/ferr079" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="contact-link" aria-label="X / Twitter — @ferr079">
              <img src="https://cdn.simpleicons.org/x/e2e8f0" alt="" class="contact-logo" loading="lazy" aria-hidden="true" onerror="this.style.display='none'" />
              <span>X / Twitter</span>
            </a>
            <a href="https://app.hackthebox.com/users/1161145" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="contact-link" aria-label="Hack The Box — Ferr079">
              <img src="https://cdn.simpleicons.org/hackthebox/9FEF00" alt="" class="contact-logo" loading="lazy" aria-hidden="true" onerror="this.style.display='none'" />
              <span>Hack The Box</span>
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</Base>

